<br>
and<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Moron rich kid brat gets to high expense school gets soemwhere in life PURELY because of the reputation of that school but he is a total idiot. Is that right?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There are some problems with that statement.  Most people in the US learn what Randul was incorrect about in free public schools.  There are private schools, but most people attend public schools.  I do agree that we need &quot;more new schools with much smaller pupil numbers and class room sizes, and higher paid and more respected teachers&quot;, but simply stating that the problem exists doesn't actually fix anything.  Besides, even with its problems, the &quot;American school system&quot; (which by the way doesn't even truely exist in such a form) isn't that bad.  There are also other problems.  If a child is raised in an environment where education isn't stressed, then no amount of education system is going to help.  <br>
<br>
As for the second quote, no its not right, but at the same time, how much does it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>truely</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> happen?  First of all, people don't get into paid schools on payment alone.  There are other factors involved such as having shown a willingness to work hard previously (previous grades, school/out of school activities, etc).  Someone who is a complete, lazy moron is going to have difficulty gaining acceptance into a paid school.  However, I'm not niave enough to believe that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>enough</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> money still wouldn't get you in.  Once in, you have a new set of problems.  If the school is truely good, then it means the students truely have to work for the grades (parent's can't just buy them).  Simply going to the school isn't good enough to get a good job, if I attend the best school in the world and get C's and D's and F's, its not going to get me a job.  If the &quot;best&quot; (considering that best <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a subjective term) school just sells grades, they will quickly lose the title of &quot;best&quot; school, and the system fixes itself.<br>
<br>
The best form of economy, in my opinion is a Capitolism that has socialism threaded through it.  Any system that is held to its extreme, literal theory will fail.  You <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>must</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> protect people from the flaws of capitolism.  For example (as Silver has brought up before) the tobacco industries have not had a very good track record.  They're starting to pay for it now, and hopefully will continue to do so.  Another example would be Enron.  A lot of good, intelligent, and completely innocent people lost their jobs because of the corruption of the heads of the company.  The government's job should then be to take care of the good workers until they can get a new job.  In pure capitolism these people would be wasted, they would go hungry, lose their homes, credit, etc, before finding a new job.  However, that doesn't mean that its the government's job to make sure everyone has money at all times.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Socialism has failed evrytime it's been tried. Thats fact. You can't name 1 place where it worked.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sweden is generally considered the model socialist society.  Of course, they also have good oil revenues, and an extremely low population, 8.9 million.  The UK is around 59 million, for comparison.<br>
<br>
Anyways, there's more I have an opinion on thats been brought up, trickle-down theory, corruption, lobbies, helping 3rd world countries, etc.  But this post is already getting so long people won't read it, so I'm going to finish up with this...<br>
<br>
Its an individual's responsibility to put clothes on their backs and a roof over their head.  Its the government's job to make sure the people have the chance to do that, while protecting them from each other.<br>
<br>
